Block Copolymers: Long-Term Growth with Added Value
O
ver the past 60 years block copolymers have evolved from a niche component to a major theme of contemporary macromolecular science and engineering. This represents the happy confluence of significant advances in several related areas: (i) controlled polymerization, beginning with living anionic polymerization in the late 1950s and expanding with ATRP, RAFT, ROMP, and others since the 1990s; (ii) facile molecular characterization, especially via NMR spectroscopy and size exclusion chromatography, since the 1970s; (iii) reliable nanostructural identification, partly via rheological means but particularly via the powerful combination of TEM and SAXS; and (iv) quantitative and accessible theory, which can both guide the search for new structures and rationalize the unexpected appearance of a previously unprecedented symmetry. This editorial is concerned primarily with this last topic, and in particular two landmark theory papers that appeared in this journal and have both inspired and guided the community in multiple, highly productive directions. The first is the legendary paper by Ludwik Leibler, “Theory of Microphase Separation in Block Copolymers”, which appeared toward the end of 1980 and has since been cited over
3200 times.1 The second is a review by Mark Matsen and Frank Bates, “Unif ying Weak- and Strong-Segregation Block Copolymer Theories”, published early in 1996 and so far cited
over 1300 times.2 Prior to considering these two papers, it is helpful to recall briefly the “state of play” in the preceding decades. Although block copolymers had been prepared as early at the 1930s, the first “deliberate” AB diblocks and ABA triblocks came from the Szwarc group, primarily to prove the success of their first living
anionic polymerization of polystyrene and polyisoprene.3 Indeed, to this day successful preparation of well-defined block polymers remains the strongest proof of a living polymerization. Self-assembly of block copolymers was studied throughout the 1960s and 1970s, notably by groups in Strasbourg and Kyoto as well as at Shell and other companies involved in commercialization. The prevalence of lamellar (L), hexagonally packed cylinders (C), and arrays of spheres (S) was well-known, primarily through TEM analysis. In fact, even
the double gyroid (G) had been seen as early as 1976,4 albeit not correctly identified until much later. At that time, the plethora of other phases accessible to diblocks was neither imagined nor suggested by experiment. For neat block copolymers the degree of segregation (quantified by the product of the volumetric degree of polymerization, N, and the segment−segment interaction parameter, χ) was typically 50 or more, placing them in what is now known as the “strong segregation regime”, where the centers of the two nanodomains are essentially either pure A or pure B. The first attempt to describe these phases with a quantitative theory was contributed by Dale Meier, who correctly captured the underlying free energy competition that drives self-assembly: balancing the interfacial energy penalty versus the entropic cost
of chain stretching.5 Gene Helfand and co-workers adopted the
self-consistent field approach pioneered by Sam Edwards6 and
under the so-called “narrow interface approximation” could capture the evolution from S → C → L → C → S with composition fA, as well as the strong-segregation scaling of
domain spacing d with N2/3.7,8 With this backdrop, Leibler’s paper appeared like a bolt from the blue. Unlike many theoretical contributions, it attempted to answer questions that had not even been asked before. It brought a coherence and a roadmap to the phase behavior of block copolymers in the bulkone that is still being vigorously pursued and refined to this day. Among the notably novel aspects of the work were the following: (i) the use of de Gennes’ random phase approximation (RPA) in block
copolymers,9 as the necessary closure relation to obtain explicit expressions for correlation functions and free energies of copolymer melts; (ii) the first reduction of the phase portrait to a universal function of (χN) and f; (iii) the first calculation of the order−disorder transition (ODT) as a function of f (which Leibler termed the microphase separation transition); (iv) the prediction that there was a critical point at (χN) ≈ 10.5 for fA = 1/2 but that otherwise the ODT would be
a first-order transition into a BCC phase; (v) systematic calculation of stability for multiple ordered phases and prediction of order−order transitions (OOTs) between phases of different symmetry (e.g., BCC → HEX; HEX → LAM); (vi) computation of the structure factor S(q) in the disordered phase, showing for the first time how SANS or SAXS could be used to obtain a quantitative measure of χ(T); (vii) recognition that fluctuations would play a strong role in the vicinity of the ODT; and (viii) the first treatment of the putative “weak-segregation” regime, where the lamellar composition profile would be closer to a sine wave than a square wave. This breakthrough paper galvanized a great deal of experimental effort, directed at preparing block copolymers with lower N and/or lower χ in order to access the ODT and the disordered melt. These studies demonstrated the power of rheology (especially the elastic modulus G′ at fixed, low
frequency) to report on the location of the ODT10 (although of course not to directly identify the ordered state
symmetry).11 The major features of the Leibler treatment were amply confirmed, but in many respects there was much more to be learned from differences between theory and experiment. One key example of this was the fact that the ODT was often a direct transition into L, C, or G, without passing through BCC. This observation is consistent with the notion that fluctuations stabilized the disordered state, such that the ODT occurred at a higher value of χN, thereby bypassing the predicted narrow window of BCC. Glenn Fredrickson and Gene Helfand proposed a pioneering fluctuation theory that rationalized many of these experimental observations, but it was not quantitatively reliable for the finite N of interest or for
a broad range of fA.12 A recent renormalized one-loop (ROL) calculation by the group of David Morse provides a more
