accurate treatment of this phenomenon,13 and direct field
theoretic simulations are also feasible.14 A second, related example was the experimental observation that the position of the peak of the disordered state structure factor, q*, varied systematically with temperature, in contrast to the temperature
independence of the Leibler model.15 This can be attributed to the onset of chain stretching well before the ODT, which is also intimately tied into the fluctuation phenomena. It also calls into question the very existence of a “weak segregation regime” in the vicinity of the ODT. In other words, the assumption that the domain spacing d would scale as N1/2 near the ODT, then transitioning to N2/3 in the strong segregation regime, needed to be reconsidered. This topic is one of many
addressed in the Matsen and Bates paper.2 By 1996 the self-consistent field theory (SCFT) was established as a reliable method for computing free energies of various ordered states; a particularly notable contribution to fast and accurate SCFT calculations was provided by Matsen
and Michael Schick.16 In a sense this is an easier task than finding the ODT reliably, which necessarily requires computing accurate free energies for both ordered and disordered states, yet SCFT can still be computationally intensive. First, a candidate symmetry is selected, and the free energy is minimized with respect to d; then, the process is repeated for all other symmetries of interest. The differences among various symmetries can be extremely subtle. One major focus of the paper is the difficulty in knowing whether G remains stable into the strong segregation regime. It turns out that even using 450 basis functions is not sufficient to answer this question with certainty, although the authors conjecture the answer is “no”. Later calculations and experiments suggest, in fact, that the answer is “yes”, or at least that G persists
beyond χN > 100.17−19 The required number of basis functions increases with χN, making this kind of analysis particularly challenging. The Matsen and Bates paper does a masterful job in comparing the approximations used in all the various theoretical approaches, which makes it of great pedagogical value. It also highlights how a deeper understanding of the various ordered states can be achieved, such as the precise composition profiles and the change in primary peak position Δq* on traversing an OOT. Although not a main focus of this paper, the authors note that conformational asymmetry can play a key role, especially given the delicate free energy balance among phases; this consideration does suggest that a truly universal phase map cannot be obtained based on χN and f alone. Nevertheless, the SCFT has to be considered one of the triumphs of soft condensed matter, providing in most cases a quantitative calculation of the free energy of any structure. It can be directly extended to include conformational asymmetry, dispersity in block lengths, multiple blocks, branched architectures, and multiple monomers. It also usable by the nonexpert, as exemplified by a recent freely downloadable
module.20 Both of these landmark papers have been crucial in advancing the ongoing duet between block copolymer experiment and theory. Since the Leiber paper appeared, several other equilibrium ordered phases have been found in AB diblocks, although this statement must be qualified by acknowledging the difficulties in proving equilibrium, both by experiment and by theory (see Figure 1). Some were anticipated first by theory, such as close-packed spheres
(FCC or HCP),21 the Fddd network phase,22 and A15,23
followed by subsequent experimental confirmation.24−26 Others were seen first in experiment, such as the double
gyroid, the Frank−Kasper σ phase,27 and a dodecagonal quasi
crystal,28 and subsequently confirmed by theory.16,29 Both of these papers remain highly relevant today, as indicated by the citation history in Figure 2. The Leibler paper has been cited over 100 times per year for the past 25 years, while the Matsen and Bates paper continues to trend upward at about 75 citations annually. Four decades after Leibler’s paper, block copolymers continue to fascinate the community. As one simple metric, approximately 10% of the papers published in this journal in 2018 contained the term “block copolymer” in the titlemore than double the frequency in 1980. Indicators such as this, and the data in Figure 2, confirm the continued growth of interest in these exemplary self-assembling macromolecules. In addition to fundamental understanding, this growth is fueled by the search for valuespecifically, high-value-added polymer materials that provide unique functionality based on prescribed nanostructure. Target applications include directed selfassembly and lithography, battery separators, fuel cell membranes, photovoltaics, nanoporous materials for filtration or catalysis, actuators, polymer gel electrolytes, gate dielectrics in organic transistors, renewable and recyclable materials,
implants, and therapeutic delivery vehicles, to name a few.10 It will be fascinating to see how many different roles block
